based on the factors we looked at (authorization, spaceship dev, customers available, weather at year end, type of launch, tourist training) we have much more confidence in SX having a successful flight compared to VG. In fact, it seems that VG would only make it with a sequence of successes and the company itself does not aim at meeting the Jan1st deadline. There is uncertainty remaining around SX. In favor of success: mainly the track record of past launches and the limited target of just going to space (vs docking on ISS). Against: weather (?). We discarded factors like COVID, customers and authorization, believing those are covered and do not represent threats.

The key aspects I'm considering are regulatory constraints, safety and engineering issues, relative priority of tourist launches to other competing operations, and track record of meeting stated mission timelines. @MCJNDU has an excellent baseline assessment. He makes the point that SpaceX consistently met timelines for getting to the ISS. I would suggest however that a civilian space flight has somewhat less priority assigned to it than a mission undertaken jointly with NASA and the immense reputational costs of failing under that scenario. That's not to say there aren't strong incentives to be first in a lucrative market. Given the SpaceX stated goal of a civilian mission no earlier than the 4th Quarter of 2021 and Virgin Galactic's recent failures, it seems SpaceX is the only company with a realistic shot. I assume a high likelihood the timeline will slip, but 1 in 4 for SpaceX seems about right.

I haven't really paid much attention to this endeavor so this research is entirely new to me.

Tough to baseline this one. SpaceX has a civilian launched planned before the end of 2021 using the Falcon 9 rocket and Dragon capsule they have successfully used with astronauts twice in 2020. Virgin Galactic had to reschedule its Dec 2020 launch and seems to be behind SpaceX as @MCJNDU pointed out. The probability that both would successfully put civilians in space in 2021 is pretty low. Would need to update this forecast as SpaceX's proposed launch date approaches.

It’s difficult to establish a base rate for this forecast as only one company has completed successful space-tourism flights. In 2001, MirCorp, a Russian spaceflight company, ferried the first space tourist to the international space station abord a Soyuz spacecraft. Russia has conducted manned launches onboard Soyuz rockets since 1968. The delay between their first successful manned flight and first space tourist flight was regulatory in nature, not technological. For SpaceX and Virgin Galactic, the opposite is true.
Note: I’m classifying civilians who fly to space, even if they receive training on how to be a crewmember, as tourists, if they paid for the space flight.

While both are technically capable of this feat, I do not think that they will receive authorization to take a civilian into space as per the definition in the question. Manned flights will happen, but not a tourist flight.

SpaceX have said they intend to launch a tourist space flight in Q4 this year but no date specified. For base rate I looked at the average delay on SpaceX launches over the last year, I gave a pass if <30days delay and a fail otherwise, this gave 16 passes and 11 fails (about 60% reliability). However I have downgraded this because the one crewed mission (May 30) was almost a year late but also as there has to be some additional uncertainty around launching members of the public (will they be fully trained, fit and ready especially as one is bring chosen by lottery) so I gave 40% for SpaceX. Virgin Galactic have much less of a track record so it's harder to tell, but the one attempt they had at launching crew to space failed. Also they have not yet specified a date in 2021 so if late even if they successfully prepare, it could slip into 2022 as s result of other random factors. I estimate at 9% but will revise upward if the two remaining test flights planned for Q1 2021 are successful. Only SpaceX is p(SpaceX)*(1-p(Virgin)), etc...

Launch: https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=070kNoEb5dU&feature=youtu.be SpaceX announced on Monday that it will launch four private individuals on a Crew Dragon capsule into orbit around the Earth, dubbed “the world’s first all-civilian mission.” It is scheduled to launch in the fourth quarter of 2021.

Both companies have historically set ambitious targets and failed to meet self-imposed timelines. Virgin Galactic seems focused on sub-orbital flights, but has had one fatal crash, and several technical issues that have delayed its goal of achieving commercial space tourism by 3+ years (originally 2018). SpaceX's goal is more ambitious, given the all-civilian crew, whose space-readiness training could take longer than anticipated, particularly given the human and PR risks of sending non-astronauts into space. However, SpaceX seems to have better technical capabilities than VG. So, overall: highest probability that neither will do it by Jan 1 '22. But if one of them does do it, it's a higher probability that SpaceX can, and the lowest probability that both VG and SpaceX do it.

* Virgin + hopes to start with commercial flights in 2021 - Virgin Galactic predicted beginning of commercial service by mid-2020 and was wrong - Virgin Galactic has incentives to be too optimistic - In Dec 12, they had severe technical issues on a test flight - COVID has interfered with earlier test flights - they plan two more test flights and a flight with Branson (which is supposed to kick off commercial operation) before starting commercial operations - Predictions about when innovative technology will be ready often tend to be too optimistic rather than too pessimistic, in particular when made by those working on the technologies.
